        <h1>Best Omelet Recipe Ever!</h1>
        <table>
            <tr>
                <th style="width:200px">Amount:</th>
                <th style="width:400px">Ingredients:</th>
                <th class="OmeleteImage" rowspan="5">
                    <img src="https://x9wsr1khhgk5pxnq1f1r8kye-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/basic-french-omelet-930x550.jpg" alt="omelet"
                        title="Omelet" width="300"/>
                </th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>2</td>
                <td>Eggs</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>2 tbsp.</td>
                <td>Milk</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>1 tbsp.</td>
                <td>Butter</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>1/4 tbsp.</td>
                <td>Salt</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Dash</td>
                <td>Pepper</td>
                <td class="Serving"><i>Serving example</i>.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <th class="Directions" colspan="2">Directions:</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td colspan="2">
                    <ol>
                    <li><b>BEAT</b> eggs, milk, salt and pepper in small bowl until blended.</li>
                    <li><b>HEAT</b> butter in 6 to 8-inch nonstick omelet pan or skillet over medium-high heat until hot. <b>TILT</b> pan to coat bottom. <b>POUR IN</b> egg mixture. Mixture should set immediately at edges.</li>
                    <li><b>GENTLY PUSH</b> cooked portions from edges toward the center with inverted turner so that uncooked eggs can reach the hot pan surface. <b>CONTINUE</b> cooking, tilting pan and gently moving cooked portions as needed.</li>
                        <li><b>SLIDE</b> omelet onto plate. <i>SERVE immediately</i>.</li>
                    </ol>
                </td>
            </tr>
        </table>
